<DOC><DOCNO> AP890310-0056 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0539EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-China-Corruption     03-10 0226</FIRST><SECOND>PM-China-Corruption,0232</SECOND><HEAD>Desire to Go Abroad Leads to Corruption, Official Paper Says</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The desire to leave China was the major cause ofthe most serious corruption cases in Shanghai, an official dailysaid today.   The China Youth News said in six of 15 cases now before Shanghaicourts, young people either embezzled money or took bribes in orderto finance a life abroad.   One 26-year-old accountant in a Shanghai embezzeled nearly$19,000 so he could study in Australia. A businessman in a textilecompany obtained $13,500 by embezzlement and bribery after he got apassport and visa.   An 23-year-old accountant in a bank embezzled $5,670 by makingfalse receipts to pay for her way out of China.   The report said next most common were cases of people takingbribes in connection with construction contracts.   One deputy general manager of a construction company receivedmore than $27,000 in bribes for subcontracting work for a ChineseAcademy of Sciences building.   Another man, named a ``construction hero'' for his good deeds forShanghai, was charged with taking $35,100 in bribes.   China is now waging a nationwide campaign against corruption,which has become increasingly serious in recent years because ofshortages of commodity goods and raw materials, rough edges in thenew market economy, and price discrepancies betweengovernment-controlled items and those selling on free markets.</TEXT></DOC>